      <h1>Coach's Speech Template & Tips</h1>
      <p>A seven-minute speech structure that hits every note.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="page-wrapper">
        <p class="lead">The coach's speech is the centerpiece of any sports banquet. It sets the tone for the entire evening. A great speech balances humor, heart, and recognition — and leaves everyone feeling proud of what the team accomplished.</p>

        <p>Here's a proven structure that works for any sport, any team size, and any season outcome.</p>

        <h2>The Formula: 4 Parts, 7 Minutes</h2>
        <table>
          <tr>
            <th>Part</th>
            <th>Time</th>
            <th>Purpose</th>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>1. Welcome & Gratitude</td>
            <td>1 min</td>
            <td>Thank everyone for coming</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2. Season Story</td>
            <td>2 min</td>
            <td>Tell the arc of the season</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>3. Team Moments</td>
            <td>2 min</td>
            <td>2-3 specific stories or memories</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>4. Closing & Send-Off</td>
            <td>2 min</td>
            <td>Inspire and transition to awards</td>
          </tr>
        </table>

        <h2>Fill-in-the-Blank Template</h2>

        <h3>Part 1: Welcome & Gratitude</h3>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"Good evening everyone. Thank you all for being here tonight to celebrate the [team name] [season/year] season.</p>
          <p>I want to start by thanking [assistant coaches/volunteers/boosters] for all the work they put in behind the scenes. This season would not have been possible without you.</p>
          <p>And to the parents — thank you for trusting us with your athletes. We know the early mornings, late practices, and weekend tournaments don't happen without your support."</p>
        </blockquote>

        <h3>Part 2: The Season Arc</h3>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"This season started with [opening game/tournament] and it feels like it flew by. We finished with a record of [record], but numbers only tell part of the story.</p>
          <p>What I'll remember most is how this team [key characteristic — never quit, grew together, fought through adversity].</p>
          <p>We had [high point of season] and we had [challenge]. But through it all, this group [positive team quality]."</p>
        </blockquote>

        <h3>Part 3: Specific Moments</h3>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"I want to share a couple moments that defined this season for me.</p>
          <p>[Story 1 — a specific game, practice, or team moment that shows who this team was]</p>
          <p>[Story 2 — a moment that made you proud as a coach]</p>
          <p>These are the things that won't show up in the highlight reel, but they're what I'll remember."</p>
        </blockquote>

        <h3>Part 4: Closing & Transition</h3>
        <blockquote>
          <p>"To our seniors — [senior name], [senior name], [senior name] — thank you for your leadership and commitment. You leave a legacy that [younger teammate or coach] will carry forward.</p>
          <p>This team [one sentence that captures the spirit of the season]. I'm proud of every single one of you.</p>
          <p>Now, let's get to what we're all here for — recognizing our athletes."</p>
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Delivery Tips</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Practice out loud</strong> — Read it three times before the event. You'll sound natural, not robotic.</li>
          <li><strong>Bring notes on index cards</strong> — Bullet points, not a script. The banquet is warm, not a lecture.</li>
          <li><strong>Make eye contact</strong> — Look at the team, not the podium. Scan the room.</li>
          <li><strong>Pause after laughs</strong> — If you get a laugh, let it breathe before continuing.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep it under 8 minutes</strong> — Attention spans are short. Leave them wanting more.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't apologize</strong> — Never start with "I'm not good at public speaking." Own the room.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>What to Avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Inside jokes only the team gets</strong> — Families and guests won't follow and will feel left out</li>
          <li><strong>Negative moments</strong> — The banquet is for celebration. Save constructive feedback for private conversations</li>
          <li><strong>Reading stats for 5 minutes</strong> — Share a few key numbers, not a stat sheet</li>
          <li><strong>Comparing this team to past teams</strong> — Each team deserves its own moment</li>
        </ul>

